Park the car in a shady spot and wait until the car's surface is cool to the touch. Use a deep-pile terrycloth microfiber towel which will trap contaminants and not grind them into the car's surface. Tip: Use two pails — one with sudsy cleaner, the other with water — when you clean. After you dip your cloth into the sudsy water and clean a portion of the car, dip the dirty, sudsy water into the pail with water so that you don't contaminate the cleaning pail. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e3/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e3/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Dishwashing detergent strips the polymers off the paint surface and accelerates the oxidation process. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/77/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Work from the top down, washing and rinsing a section at a time. Do not allow soap to dry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Take the spray nozzle off the water hose before doing a final rinse to minimize spots. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet4.jpg/v4-460px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/17/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet4.jpg/v4-760px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a chamois or terry cloth towel to dry; do not let air-dry or soap spots will form. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet5.jpg/v4-460px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet5.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/02/Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet5.jpg/v4-760px-Detail-a-Car-Step-16Bullet5.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
